### Per-question file shape

Each `QNN.marking.md` file must contain these sections, in order.
**Use the exact header shapes shown below** (`#### N. <Title>`)
— the publish-time parser matches these specifically, and a
different header level or unnumbered header will silently drop
the section from the rendered page.

#### 1. Question identification (3-5 lines)

- Question number (e.g. "01", "08")
- Total marks available (sum of `marks` for all criteria in this
  question, from the markscheme)
- The question sub-parts covered by the transcripts (e.g. "Q01.1,
  Q01.2, Q01.3, Q01.4, Q01.5, Q01.6" or "Q08.3 only")
- A short printed-context summary of the question (a one-sentence
  summary of what the question asks — drawn from the transcripts
  where this question is covered)

#### 2. Per-criterion marking (one block per criterion)

For EACH criterion in `markscheme.json#marks[QN].criteria`
(where QN is q1, q2, …, q{{ question_count }}), produce a block with this shape:

```
### Criterion N: <ao> -- <marks> mark(s)
**Sub-question this criterion applies to:** <qN.X -- your best
guess based on the indicative content and the transcript>
**Indicative content:** <bullet list from the markscheme>
**Transcript section covered:** <which transcript file and
which question header in it — or "not covered by any transcript"
if the criterion is for a sub-question whose page is missing>
**Decision:** AWARD | NOT_AWARD | NOT_APPLICABLE
**Marks awarded:** <integer, 0 to marks available>
**Justification:** <2-4 sentences. Quote the student's answer
where relevant. The justification is STUDENT-FACING — it will
appear on the public feedback page. Do NOT include assessor-only
process notes here (e.g. "originally NOT_AWARD but re-OCR'd with
graph-specific prompt and re-marked", "the OCR said no answer
written on this page but the photo clearly shows..."). Those go
in `assessor_notes` (see below), not here. The student only needs
to see the substantive content: what the indicative content asks
for, what the student wrote, and the gap (if any) between them.>
**Assessor notes:** <OPTIONAL. 1-3 sentences of process notes for
the assessor (Aaron) only — things that should NOT be on the
public page. Examples: "Re-OCR'd on DATE with graph-specific
prompt to recover drawn best-fit lines", "Originally NOT_AWARD
based on first OCR transcript; upgraded after assessor
re-checked page 10 against the photo", "Handwritten equation is
visually ambiguous between 7X and 8X; awarded on the strict
reading of the transcript". If there's nothing to flag, write
"None." or omit the field.>
```

**Important — verbatim quoting in the Justification:** When you
quote the student's answer, copy it from the transcript file
**exactly** — including spelling mistakes, grammar errors, and
arithmetic. Do not correct or paraphrase it. If the transcript
has `[illegible]`, write `[illegible]` in the justification.

**Important — process marks:** Many criteria in the markscheme
have "allow" clauses (e.g. "allow correct use of incorrectly
determined values of bonds broken and/or bonds made", "allow
correct evaluation of the expression energy released = bonds
broken − bonds made"). These are explicit. If a criterion has an
"allow" clause, apply it: even if the student got an earlier
step wrong, you can still award the later step *if the student
correctly applied the process to the wrong value*. Read the
transcript line by line and decide for each criterion whether
the student's answer, given his setup, is internally consistent.

**Important — coefficient and unit errors:** For calculation
questions, look for the right variables. If the student wrote a
different coefficient than the markscheme requires, the
downstream algebra marks are NOT awarded because the algebra
doesn't follow from the original setup. The "bonds made" and
"bonds broken" process marks may still be available if the
student's setup is internally consistent. Apply the markscheme
strictly.

**Important — IDK and empty answers:** Many answers are "IDK" /
"Idk" / "Not covered yet" / left blank. For these answers, every
criterion for that sub-question is NOT_AWARD with 0 marks and a
one-line justification: "Student wrote 'IDK' / left blank — no
content to assess against the indicative content." Do not
speculate about what the student might have known.

**Important — crossed-out answers:** The transcripts preserve
crossed-out words with `(crossed out)` annotation. A crossed-out
answer is NOT awarded (the student themselves invalidated it).
A new answer written *above or after* the crossed-out one IS
considered.

**Important — diagram descriptions:** Some transcripts describe
diagrams in structured form (e.g. "graph drawn with plotted
points at..."). For markscheme criteria that award marks for
correct graph features (best-fit line, points plotted, axes
labelled), check the diagram description carefully. If the
description says the student drew the line, award the mark; if
it says the student left the graph blank, do not.

**Important — not-applicable criteria:** Some criteria may
apply to sub-questions whose pages are missing or that are simply
not covered by any of the transcripts. Mark these as
NOT_APPLICABLE with a one-line justification.

#### 3. Legibility assessment (one block, 6 lines)

This is a **risk signal**, not a re-grade. Per-question legibility
captures how hard the handwriting was to read. The marking
decisions above stand; this section asks: *could a tired but fair
GCSE examiner have read this answer quickly enough to award the
mark without heroic reconstruction?*

For this question, write a `### Legibility` block with exactly
these fields (use the literal `Field:` prefixes so the parser
can find them):

```
### Legibility

**legibility_score:** <integer 0-5>
**ocr_mode:** <one of: clear_read | minor_uncertainty | context_inferred | unreadable>
**reason:** <one short sentence, ~10-20 words, explaining what made this question easy or hard to read>
**student_feedback:** <one short sentence, ~10-20 words, written directly to Will in second person ("Your handwriting...", "You wrote..."), giving specific actionable advice>
```

**legibility_score scale (anchor with the GC: would a tired
GCSE examiner read this quickly without heroic reconstruction?):**
- **5** = Clean print or fully legible joined-up writing; no
  hesitation. A tired examiner reads it instantly.
- **4** = Standard legible handwriting. A tired examiner reads
  it without slowing down.
- **3** = Readable but slow. A tired examiner has to pause on
  one or two words, but reconstructs them without help.
- **2** = Readable only because context fills the gap. A tired
  examiner would not award the mark on the handwriting alone —
  the markscheme or the surrounding answer had to do work.
- **1** = Heroic reconstruction needed. The transcript had
  `[illegible]` markers, or the examiner would have to guess
  what was meant from partial letters.
- **0** = Genuinely cannot read. Multiple words or the whole
  answer are unreadable.

**ocr_mode is derived from legibility_score:**
- score 4-5 → `clear_read`
- score 3 → `minor_uncertainty`
- score 2 → `context_inferred`
- score 0-1 → `unreadable`

**Do NOT use `forensic_reconstruction` (or any other label)**
— the four options above are the only valid values.

**Do NOT modify the per-criterion marking based on legibility.**
If the transcript says `[illegible]` and you NOT_AWARD a
criterion because of it, note that in the criterion's
justification (and in the Assessor notes section's "OCR
blockers" list) — do NOT inflate the legibility score to make
the marking look less risky. Legibility reflects the
handwriting; marking reflects the markscheme. They are
independent.

**Do NOT inflate the score because the markscheme was
forgiving.** A question where the student wrote one word and
it happened to match the rubric still gets a low legibility
score if that one word was hard to read.

**student_feedback is written to Will, not about Will.** Use
second person ("Your handwriting on the Q1.5 percentage-yield
calculation was hard to read — the '92.8' looked like '92.0'
at first glance. Print your key numbers more clearly."),
not third person ("The student would benefit from..."). Be
specific: name the question, the kind of error, and the
fix. Skip the praise; Will doesn't need it. One short
sentence is enough.

#### 4. Question summary (2-3 lines)

- **Total marks awarded for this question:** `<sum of marks
  awarded for all criteria, integer>` out of `<total marks for
  this question>`.
- **One sentence on what cost the most marks** (e.g. "Student got
  4/8 on Q1, with 3 marks lost on the percentage-yield calculation
  where they did not set up the equation correctly").
- **Legibility summary (one short sentence):** e.g. "Question
  was generally legible (score 4/5); the calculation on Q1.5
  was the only slow spot."

### Summary file shape

The `SUMMARY.md` file must contain, in order. **Use the exact
header shapes shown below** (`#### N. <Title>`) — the
publish-time parser matches these specifically, and a different
header level or unnumbered header will silently drop the
section from the rendered page. Specifically, the four section
headers MUST be exactly:

```
#### 1. Paper header
#### 2. Per-question tally table
#### 3. Cross-paper observations
#### 4. Assessor notes
```

Lower-case, unnumbered, hyphenated ("## Cross-paper
observations"), or differently-cased variants will be silently
dropped. The "Cross-paper observations" section is student-
facing; the "Assessor notes" section is assessor-only and is
not surfaced on the public page.

#### 1. Paper header (3-4 lines)

- Paper code
- Sitting
- Total marks available ({{ total_marks }})
- Total marks awarded (`<sum across all {{ question_count }} Q-NN.marking.md files, integer>`)

#### 2. Per-question tally table (one row per Q)

A markdown table with columns: `Question | Marks available | Marks
awarded | Notes`. One row per Q1-Q{{ question_count }}. Notes column is a
one-sentence summary of the question's marking (e.g. "Strong on the
conceptual prose, lost marks on calculations").

#### 3. Cross-paper observations (3-5 short paragraphs, STUDENT-FACING)

A few short paragraphs (each 2-4 sentences) on cross-cutting
patterns you noticed while marking. The student reads this on the
public page, so write it in second person ("You did better on…")
and keep it substantive. Patterns to cover:

- **Calculation vs prose:** Did the student do better on prose
  answers (where they could express a concept in their own words)
  or on calculations (where the markscheme has specific numerical
  answers)? Give specific examples.
- **Pattern of "IDK" answers:** How many sub-questions did the
  student skip or write "IDK" on? Were they clustered in any
  topic? (E.g. "You wrote IDK on 3 of 5 calculation questions in
  Q4, but attempted all the prose questions in Q5.")

#### 4. Assessor notes (assessor-only; not on the public page)

The following paragraphs are pipeline meta. They describe the OCR +
marking chain's behaviour, not the student's work. They live in
this section so the assessor (Aaron) can audit a marking pass, but
they are NOT surfaced on the rendered feedback page.

- **OCR blockers / human review list:** If you had to NOT_AWARD a
  criterion because the transcript said `[illegible]` or had low
  confidence, list the affected questions here. This is the "human
  review" list — these are the marks that should be re-checked
  against the original photos by a human. Cross-reference each
  entry with the question's `legibility_score` and `ocr_mode`
  (e.g. "Q07.2 (legibility_score=1, ocr_mode=unreadable): the
  one word after 'different sized' is illegible; recheck the
  photo").
- **Legibility overview:** A 1-2 sentence summary of legibility
  across the paper (e.g. "Q3 was the cleanest (5/5); Q7 had
  the most illegible spots (3/5 average, 1/5 on Q7.2)."). This
  is a rollup — the per-Q scores are in the Q-NN files.
- **Marking uncertainty:** Criteria where you had to NOT_AWARD with
  a justification like "could go either way" or "the transcript is
  ambiguous" go here. These are the marks the *marking model* is
  uncertain about, even when the transcript is clear.
- **Pipeline verdict:** Did the OCR + markscheme chain produce
  marks you would defend to a real GCSE marker? (yes / mostly /
  no). What would improve the marking fidelity? (e.g. "human
  review on the 5 calculation pages where the OCR flagged
  `[illegible]`", "second-pass OCR on the harder pages", "use a
  chemistry-domain model instead of a general one"). One sentence
  on whether this batch pipeline is ready to be run on the next
  paper with minimal changes.

## Hard rules

- **Do not commit.** Do not push. Do not `git add` anything.
- **Do not run any network command.** No curl, no pip install, no
  git fetch, no `codex login`, nothing.
- **Do not modify any file outside the {{ question_count + 1 }} output
  files** ({{ question_count }} Q-NN.marking.md + 1 SUMMARY.md). Specifically:
  - Do not edit the transcript files.
  - Do not edit the markscheme file.
  - Do not edit any other file in the repo.
- **Do not invent markscheme criteria.** Apply only the criteria
  that exist in `markscheme.json#marks[*].criteria[*]`. There are
  exactly {{ criteria_count }} criteria across {{ question_count }}
  questions; do not add more.
- **Do not give the student the benefit of the doubt on the
  basis of "what they probably meant".** If the student's algebra
  uses a different coefficient than the rubric, that is a missing
  mark. Quote the rubric.
- **Do not re-grade the markscheme.** Apply it as written. If you
  think a criterion is unfair, note that in the Assessor notes
  section, but do not change the mark.
- **If you cannot do this task for any reason**, write `BLOCKED` at
  the top of EACH marking file you have not yet completed, and
  explain in one paragraph why. Do not silently fall back to a
  half-done marking.

